com.siperian.sif.message.mrm

Class PutRequest

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.siperian.sif.message.SiperianRequest
      • com.siperian.sif.message.mrm.PutRequest
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    DataProvider, RecordKeyProvider, SiperianObjectUidProvider, Serializable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    PutDependentObjectRequest

    public class PutRequest
extends SiperianRequest
implements SiperianObjectUidProvider, RecordKeyProvider, DataProvider
    Inserts or updates a single record identified by a key into a base object. The base object used is the primary table in the put-enabled package specified.

    For base objects or packages with state management enabled, state can be specified when inserting a new record. State management is enabled on a package by enabling state management on the parent base object of the package in the Hub Console. Packages with state management enabled will have a column called HUB_STATE_IND. When inserting a new record, a value can be specified for the HUB_STATE_IND column that will be used as the initial state of the new record. The possible values for HUB_STATE_IND are 1, 0, and -1 corresponding to ACTIVE, PENDING, and DELETED states respectively. The Put API cannot be used to change the state of an existing record. If a value is provided for the HUB_STATE_IND column when updating an existing record, the Put API will throw an exception. To change the state of an existing record, refer to the javadocs for the following classes: DeleteRequest, RestoreRequest, and PromotePendingXrefsRequest.

    Required Parameters:

    • setRecordKey(RecordKey) - Specifies the key of the record to be updated or inserted. This is used to uniquely identify both base object and cross reference records. The SystemName field must be specified in order to identify the cross reference record.

    • setRecord(Record) - Contains the data to be updated or inserted. The SiperianObjectUid field for the record (see Record.setSiperianObjectUid(String)) specifies the type and the name of the base object or put-enabled package used to identify the affected base object and constrain the fields that can be set.

    The record can contain all or a subset of the base object or package fields. For example, a package may contain fields FIRST_NAME and LAST_NAME. If only the last name is being updated the FIRST_NAME field can be omitted.

    A successful Put operation can have one of the following results:

    • Insert - A cross reference record and an associated base object record are inserted.
    • Update - A cross reference record and its base object record are updated. The effect on the base object depends on the trust configuration for updated fields.
    • Insert Xref - A cross reference record is inserted and associated with an existing base object. The base object fields are updated based on the trust configuration.

    Usage Example:

    The following example updates a record with ROWID_OBJECT key 782 using the package ADDRESS_UPDATE.

    PutRequest request = new PutRequest();
    request.setRecordKey(RecordKey.rowid("782", "SALES"));
    Record record = new Record();
    record.setSiperianObjectUid(SiperianObjectType.PACKAGE.makeUid("ADDRESS_UPDATE"));
    record.setField( new Field("ADDRESS_LINE1", "123 Main St.") );
    record.setField( new Field("CITY", "Anytown") );
    request.setRecord( record );
    PutResponse response = (PutResponse) sipClient.process(request);

    Each Record is made up of a list of Fields (name / value pairs). If the base object column corresponding to a Field is trust enabled, the trust value for the column is based on the trust setting for that column and system. The default trust settings can be overridden by using a TrustOverrideField in the Record rather than a Field. TrustOverrideField.setTrustOverride(TrustSetting) is used to define the custom trust setting for the Field.

    A package can contain system columns and columns marked as read-only. The Record can not include Fields for these. System columns are those that are automatically added to a base object and are managed by the Hub - CREATOR, CREATE_DATE, UPDATED_BY, LAST_UPDATE_DATE, CONSOLIDATION_IND, DELETED_IND, DELETED_BY, DELETED_DATE, LAST_ROWID_SYSTEM, DIRTY_IND, INTERACTION_ID.

    Optional Parameters:

    • setLastUpdateDate(Date) - The request can specify a last update date for the record. If not specified the current date and time are used. If specified, the value must not be later than the current date and time.
    • setGenerateSourceKey(boolean) - This parameter is useful for keyless systems (for example, an application that does not persist source data). When set to true, a source key is generated if one is not already specified.
    • setBypassPostLoadUE(boolean) - This parameter is useful for controlling whether or not to execute the post load user exit (if one exists). The post load user exit gets executed by the PL/SQL put procedure. When set to true, the post load user exit will be bypassed.
    • setPeriodStartDate(Date) - This parameter is use to specified period start date for versioning.
    • setPeriodEndDate(Date) - This parameter is use to specified end date for versioning.
    This table describes what happens with various RecordKey combinations when GenerateSourceKey = false.

    RecordKeyHow record is resolvedResults
    rowid Look for a cross reference for this rowid and system. Found - updates the cross reference and base object records.

    Not found - inserts a cross reference record with sourceKey = input rowid and updates the base object record.

    sourceKey Look for a cross reference for this sourceKey and system. Found - updates the cross reference and base object records.

    Not found - inserts a cross reference record with specified sourceKey and inserts a base object record.

    rowid & sourceKey Look for a cross reference for this rowid, sourceKey and system. Found - updates the cross reference and base object records.

    Not found - inserts a cross reference record with specified sourceKey and updates the base object record.

    sourceKey & periodStartDate/periodEndDate Look for a cross reference for this sourceKey and system and periodStartDate/periodEndDate (versioning only). Found - updates the cross reference and base object records.

    Not found - inserts a cross reference record with specified sourceKey and inserts a base object record.

    rowidXref Look for a cross reference for this rowidXref. Found - updates the cross reference and base object records if the record is active periodStartDate/periodEndDate are the same or if the record is pending update the xref and possible change the period.

    Not found - an error is returned

    GBID Look for a unique cross reference with this GBID value and system. Found - updates the cross reference and base object records.

    Not found - error - GBID must resolve to an existing record.

    This table describes what happens with various RecordKey combinations when GenerateSourceKey = true

    RecordKeyHow record is resolvedResults
    rowid Look for a base object for this rowid and system. Found - inserts a cross reference with generated sourceKey and updates the base object record.

    Not found - error - rowid must resolve to an existing record.

    sourceKey Look for a cross reference for this sourceKey and system. Same as in table above. sourceKey provided is used.
    rowid & sourceKey Look for a cross reference for this rowid, sourceKey, and system. Same as in table above. sourceKey provided is used.
    GBID Look for a unique cross reference with this GBID value and system. Found - inserts a cross reference with generated sourceKey and updates the base object record.

    Not found - error - GBID must resolve to an existing record.

    Transaction Support

    When executed within an EJB context, this request can be part of a transaction with other requests. If there is a failure in any of the requests within a transaction, the entire transaction is rolled back.

    Note: Both Put and Cleanse Put requests process null values; for example when no value is specified for a field, it will be set to null.

    See Also:
    DeleteRequest, RestoreRequest, PromotePendingXrefsRequest, PutResponse, Serialized Form

    API Pair: PutResponse

    API Group: Data Update/Insert
